Comment: Dear Governor Perdue, I am writing to appeal to you to please make exceptions to this rule for those children affected by the date change who were already born when this bill was signed and whose parents had already planned on enrolling them in school in the Fall of 2009. (Children born between September 1st and October 16th 2004(for Kindergarten) and 2005 (for Pre-K)). My children attend Highland Mill Montessori, one of the magnet schools in the Charlotte Mecklenburg School System. This school has a Pre-K program, that while is not federally funded (parents pay tuition for their children to attend), must be processed through the CMS enrollment office. This is my son’s third year at HMM (Pre-K, K, 1st grade) and he loves it. We had known since my daughter was born on October 6th, 2005, that she would enroll in the Pre-K program at HMM in the Fall of 2009. We knew when we planned our pregnancy with our second baby that we wanted them to be three years apart and also three grades apart. Even though she went a week past her due date, we were relieved that she still made the NC cut-off date and would be able to go to school as planned. You can imagine our dismay when we learned in 2007 that the State had decided to change the cut off date effective the year she was supposed to begin. All our life plans had now been shifted by a year and my daughter’s life had been essentially put “on hold” for a year. My birthday is the end of September and began a pre-K program when I was 3, soon to be 4 and was always ahead of most of my peers in academics, so I have personal experience with being among the youngest in my grade. My daughter is exceptionally sharp and is more than ready to begin Pre-K in the Fall. Please let me know what I can do to help with this process. I know I am not the only parent out there whose child made the old cut-off date but misses the new one and is frustrated with their choices. I have tried to enroll my child in CMS for the Fall and our application was rejected due to the cut-off date change. I have spoken with the Magnet Office, reminding them that this is NOT a federally funded program, PLEASE let her in, but they say their hands are tied by the rulings of the General Assembly and the mandates from the NC Department of Instruction in Raleigh. Please allow the children born within those 6 ½ weeks, whose parents want them to start school “on-time”,to be grandfathered in to the current cut-off date. If that is not possible, please let them be tested to see if they are ready or sign a waiver that if they begin school and the teachers decide they are not ready, the parents will pull them out (Currently there is a test for early Kindergarten, but not early Pre-K). I am very frustrated by this and I know I am not the only one. Thank you for your time, and I hope to hear back from each of you. Kierstin Boujlil

