Comment: ¡°Thanks, Randy. You have some great stories to share that demonstrate the important role adults play in the lives of young people. You also had some great advice given to you from mentors throughout your career that you took to heart. I appreciate your sharing¡± (Bill Harrison, Chief Executive of North Carolina¡¯s K-12 System and Chairman of the State Board of Education). After Mr. Harrison read what I wrote below, I received this (the above) from him on 2/18/09. I thought you might be interested in reading it. Randy _________________________________________ Reaching the Student¡¯s Mind by Reaching the Student¡¯s Heart by Randy Yost "The nature of the work of teachers has changed dramatically from my time as a student, to my time as a teacher, to my time as a principal, to my time as a superintendent, and it will continue to change. However, as the way we do our work changes, the one constant that has remained from my time as a student until today, and will always remain, is student success comes down to a competent, caring teacher in the classroom. "Every time I visit a classroom, no matter what the grade or subject, my belief is reinforced. Teachers make the difference. Children come to us in all shapes and sizes, from all types of backgrounds. I recognize teachers are enriching their lives in ways those outside of the school may never know. When I think back to my days in the public schools of Pennsylvania, there is much I do not remember. What I do remember are the names of the teachers I had and how they shaped my life." (Bill Harrison, Chief Executive of North Carolina¡¯s K-12 System and Chairman of the State Board of Education) I will never forget one of my high school juniors, a 16 year-old male student. I was teaching English, and he came in late for my class. When I asked him why he was tardy, he could not tell me because he was crying---right in front of about 30 other students. After he sat down, I walked to his desk and asked him what was wrong. ¡°Mr. Yost, my mother died when I was 5. Now my father has cancer,¡± he said. After my heart fell to my stomach, I told the students to answer the questions at the end of Thoreau¡¯s ¡°From Walden.¡± (I was teaching Thoreau¡¯s ¡°From Walden.¡±) Unlike the other students who began working, this student did not begin working. Instead, again, he was crying. I wrote some words on a piece of paper. Then I handed the paper to him. Although he did not stop crying, he stopped crying aloud. While I stood behind the podium and stared at this student, I thought about another junior, a 17-year old female student, who walked up to me one day while I was teaching. I stopped teaching and asked her what was wrong. She started crying and said she was upset because one of her girlfriends had sex with her father (the father of the girl who was crying). She asked me if she could go to the bathroom. I told another female student to go with her. While I was thinking about this student, the bell rang and the students left the room. Then I sat at my desk and thought about another high school student, a ¡°hard core¡± student, who told me the following: ¡°Mr. Yost, I have never seen my parents. Both of them are in prison. I have lived from foster home to foster home.¡± As I thought about this student¡¯s life, I said to myself, ¡°No wonder this student is ¡®hard core¡¯.¡± I have worked as a public school educator for almost 20 years. Today I work as the coordinator of a public school¡¯s intervention center. We serve 5 different schools: a high school, a middle school, and three elementary schools. I work with principals, several assistant principals, and MANY teachers. I also work with school counselors and parents. I receive on average about 20 e-mails per day, and the telephone rings on average about 15 times per day. Although I no longer teach in the classroom or give grades, I still work with students as a ¡°counselor¡± and a ¡°tutor.¡± Therefore, I continue to experience similar stories---like the ones I shared that I heard from students while teaching in the classroom for many years. For example, recently I had a female middle school student who lives at a group home and a male high school student who lives at a different group home. One day at the Intervention Center the female student cut herself and stuck a pencil eraser in her ear, so I had to call the middle school and tell them she was trying to hurt herself. Due to her continual unhappiness and so her self-inflicted wounds, she was placed in a state hospital. On a different day at the Intervention Center, the male student told me repeatedly that he wanted to go home; and he asked me a couple times to talk with his lawyer about getting him out of his group home. When he found out that his parents said he had to stay in the group home, one night at the group home he shut the door to his room, lay on his bed, and set his blanket on fire: he wanted to burn up his room, thus killing himself. He came back to the Intervention Center about two weeks later; and then three weeks after returning, I called the group home one morning because he did not come to the Intervention Center that morning. That afternoon one of the counselors from the group home came to see me, and he told me that this student would not be back because he tried to kill himself by hanging himself. On my way home that afternoon, I called his dad and talked with him for several minutes. He said his son was placed in a state hospital. Then there are the students who tell me that they have not seen their mom or dad in several months, since they are living with one parent and their parents will not even speak to each other. Recently, for example, I had to call a school counselor about a 14 year-old female student who would NOT stop crying: she was emotionally shipwrecked due to her mother¡¯s hatred and her father¡¯s hatred for each other, a hatred for each other that started after the father had an affair with (and moved in with) his mother-in-law (this girl¡¯s grandmother or this girl¡¯s mother¡¯s mom). The counselor had to take this student to her office, and the last thing I heard is that this student is still emotionally shipwrecked. These true stories clearly show that many young people are really hurting. Many young people have in-depth emotional problems (heart problems), and one can see why. In fact, due to their widespread heart problems, I am convinced that ESPECIALLY TODAY educators must reach the student¡¯s heart IF we are going to reach the student¡¯s mind. (I have talked with MANY educators who feel the same way---that we must reach the student¡¯s heart IF we are going to reach the student¡¯s mind.) Do not misunderstand me: students need to learn English, math, science, history, etc; and I promote this because I am a public school educator---a North Carolina certified teacher with a M.A. degree also. Further, I write and read DAILY. I am also a strong advocate of reading, writing, and discussing in order to grow intellectually and socially. Also, I believe every student should know how to communicate and how to think (to reason logically) in writing and orally before they graduate from high school. Also, do not misunderstand me: I know that disrespect and laziness are NOT to be tolerated---period. In other words, in writing this paper I am NOT advocating that educators should allow their students to be disrespectful or lazy in light of their plight. I am absolutely NOT saying (promoting) this! In fact, those who know me know that I implement ¡°tough love¡± whenever (not if) it is necessary. This, too, is why four years ago the principal of the high school who was in charge of the intervention center agreed to move me out of the classroom to work as the coordinator of the intervention center---that is, as he saw me teach in the classroom and as we talked about it four years ago, he knew that I employ ¡°tough love¡± whenever it is necessary. (Since I helped my wife raise a daughter [who is now grown], and since my wife and I are now raising our teenage son, I know that at times young people need [and they really want] ¡°tough love.¡±) Still, I also know from experience that ESPECIALLY TODAY¡¯S typical students have a lot of heart-felt issues due to the kinds of experiences I have shared. Therefore without any intervention, they could care less about knowing, for example, the difference between an adverb and an adjective---that an adverb modifies a verb, adverb, or an adjective while an adjective modifies a noun or pronoun. In fact, their heartfelt issues make learning grammatical issues a real ¡°issue¡± with them. Without any intervention, these students could care less about knowing, for instance, the difference between the perimeter and the area of a geometric figure, such as a rectangular. Instead, the size of the pain in their hearts makes the size of geometric figures unimportant in comparison. Without any intervention, these students could care less about knowing, for example, the difference between the First Law of Thermodynamics and the Second Law of Thermodynamics. Their dynamite problems prevent them from seeing the ¡°dynamics¡± of the Laws of Thermodynamics. Without any intervention, these students could care less about knowing, for instance, the difference between the Legislative Branch (law making branch) and the Executive Branch of the United States Government, or that the Executive Branch executes (carries out, not makes) the laws that have been legislated by the Legislative Branch. Their heart-felt problems have been ¡°executed¡± so they shun that which has anything to do with having ¡°laws.¡± Although, again, students need to know these academic things and students need to respect their teachers and not be lazy, today¡¯s typical middle school and high school students, such as the ones I describe above, could care less about knowing these things. Instead, they want to know (even if their ¡°want to¡± is subconsciously) that educators care about them---their problems---or that we perceive them as human beings as such and not just as students per se. My experience, in fact, confirms that we will not teach today¡¯s typical students (or reach their minds) until we first reach their hearts by letting them know that we care about them and hence that they are human beings as such. So in order to reach the minds of students, how can we reach their hearts by letting them know that we care about them (their problems) and thus that they are human beings as such? What is the intervention? First, we must befriend students. About 20 years ago, a wise high school principal told me the following: ¡°Randy, you cannot be a student¡¯s pal; but you can and must be a student¡¯s friend. Being a student¡¯s pal does not allow you to maintain the teacher-student relationship (hierarchy) that is imperative for success in the academic realm, but being a student¡¯s friend allows and enables success in the academic realm.¡± My 20 years of experience confirm that he is correct. Befriending students, which requires talking with students as a friend (as we do with other friends), lets them know that we care about them and/or that we care about their problems---that they are human beings first and students second. That is, not only must it be that it is students first and then athletes second---that they are student-athletes and not athlete-students---but also it must be that they are human beings first and students second. In other words, again, students must know that we care about their problems, their heartaches, their difficulties, their sorrows---that we do NOT look beyond these human being-related experiences because we see them as only students. Instead, again, we must talk with them as a friend also in order for them to perceive that we deem them as human beings first and students second. This means that neither do we talk ¡°down to them¡± as though they are second-rate because ¡°they are the student and we are the teacher.¡± Once they know that we care about them as human beings as such, or that we are their friends, then we will have access to their minds because we have obtained access to their hearts. Here is the principle: since young people are human beings also, the clich¨¦ that people do not care about how much you know until they know how much you care applies to them too. I mean, we must befriend them and hence show them that we care about them (reaching their hearts) as human beings first before we show them what they can and need to know as students (reaching their minds). Second, Zig Ziglar has always been one of my favorite motivational speakers. I am a stalwart believer and promoter of one of his prominent sayings: People were "designed for accomplishment, engineered for success, and endowed with the seeds of greatness." As Ziglar believes, since human beings were designed, human beings have a Designer; and as Ziglar believes (his office e-mailed me and confirmed this), the Designer is God (This is NOT a reference to religion as such) who designed humankind to be successful and, therefore, endowed human beings with the seeds (ability/talent) to do great things. In other words, every student is a human being, so God has designed every student to succeed since God designed every human being to succeed (Again, this is NOT a reference to religion as such). Frankly, our belief in this makes the first thing a lot easier: if we believe that God designed human beings with the ability to succeed and students are human beings who thus have been designed by God with the ability to succeed, it will not be difficult to befriend every student as a human being as such due to the parity that exists between students and us---the God-given ability for humanity (all of us) to succeed. If young people know (and if we know) that they are wonderfully designed because, as Ziglar believes, they came from (were designed from) the Designer God, they will know that they have intrinsic value in just being created as a human being. Rick Warren, the author of the book Purpose Driven Life and the person who PRAYED at PRESIDENT OBAMA's Inauguration because PRESIDENT OBAMA ASKED him to pray, says the following about human beings: "God is more interested in what I am than in what I do. That's why we are called human beings, not human doings." In other words, the emphasis must be on the "being" (a human being) and not on the "doing"---a student doing math work, doing English work, doing science work, doing history work, etc. The truism that young people are human beings foremost with inherent value will nurture the doing as students, since the "doing" is the result of the "being" (human beings). Their social behavior will be affected also because what is manifested outwardly comes from what exists inwardly, as output is based on input. Alas! When will we see the significance of young people perceiving themselves with intrinsic value in being created (designed) by God to succeed?!? Again and again, this is not a reference to religion as such. Just ask President Obama, who publicly says he believes in God and thus asked Minister Rick Warren to pray at his Inauguration! Not only am I failing to advocate religion as such, but also neither am I promoting that educators of any religion ¡°witness¡± to students in the public school classroom because this is deemed illegal by the government. Although it is legal to teach about religion in the public school classroom, it is not legal to teach in religion: ¡°To teach about religion is not to instruct in religion. Teaching about religion embraces the study of various religions¡­.Instruction in religion, by contrast, is to seek acceptance of and commitment to a particular religion¡± [California Department of Education]. In other words, public school educators of any religion should not evangelize in the classroom, ¡°witnessing¡± to students. This is not legally permitted. Anyway, many young people have in-depth emotional problems (heart problems). Due to their widespread heart problems, I am convinced that ESPECIALLY TODAY educators must reach the student¡¯s heart IF we are going to reach the student¡¯s mind. That is, we must intervene and befriend them as human beings first and students second. Of course, again and again, this does NOT mean that we condone disrespect and laziness. We must also intervene and reflect that they have been designed to succeed and to do great things. I know MANY educators who REALLY CARE about their students, and many of these have told me that they agree with what I have written. I respect the many educators who have told me this; and I respect the many other educators who likewise believe what Bill Harrison, Chief Executive of North Carolina¡¯s K-12 System, says: ¡°Student success comes down to a competent, caring teacher in the classroom¡­.Teachers make the difference.¡±

